{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504347","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504347"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:14:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:14:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2324"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2324"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.72,0.04,0.09,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2324"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106986"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2324"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2324"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89450"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1396"},{"type":"tags","id":"1976"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1067"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1086"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1204"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38071"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39433"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44943"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106986"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 30-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with acute nasal obstruction, nasal deformity and minor bilateral epistaxis. These symptoms have developed five days after an injury to his nose. He was assessed at the Emergency Department on the day of injury and was diagnosed with acute fractures of the nasal bones with no other facial or intra-cranial injuries identified. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the nasal dorsum is deviated to the right. A purple, boggy swelling is present on both sides of the septum, occluding both nostrils. The nasal septum is deviated to the right. No neurological or other bony injuries are identified.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important cause to exclude?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Deviation of a fractured nasal septum","Septal haematoma","Bilateral inferior turbinate hypertrophy","Bilateral nasal valve collapse","Saddle deformity of the nasal septum"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient reporting bilateral nasal obstruction in the days following nasal trauma requires prompt examination to exclude a \u003Cstrong\u003Eseptal haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E. Septal haematoma is a significant complication which if left untreated, may progress to abscess and ischaemic necrosis of the septal cartilage. They occur following rupture of blood vessels supplying the septal cartilage and collection of blood between the avascular cartilage and the overlying mucosa. Once septal haematoma has been excluded, uncomplicated nasal fractures may be managed with closed reduction under either local or general anaesthetic. Patients with a suspected fracture should be referred to an ENT service for review, within 7-10 days of the injury where possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDeviation due to a fractured nasal septum\u003C/strong\u003E is more likely to cause unilateral obstruction once initial swelling improves after approximately five days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with \u003Cstrong\u003Ebilateral inferior turbinate hypertrophy\u003C/strong\u003E classically report intermittent obstruction of one or both nostrils, often swapping sides at different times of day or with the patient in different positions. It may be associated with allergic rhinitis and hay fever symptoms. It is usually unrelated to nasal trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollapse of the internal nasal valve\u003C/strong\u003E is typically a chronic issue relating to laxity of the lower lateral cartilages, deviation of the nasal septum, or hypertrophy of the inferior turbinate. Any or all of these can contribute to either unilateral or bilateral dynamic collapse of the internal nasal valve.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESaddle deformity\u003C/strong\u003E is a defect of the dorsum of the quadrangular cartilage of the septum. It typically results from autoimmune destruction of the cartilage, following rhinoplasty surgery, or as a late complication of an untreated septal haematoma resulting in loss of the septal cartilage.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bilateral nasal obstruction after a nasal injury is likely to be due to a septal haematoma.","Septal haematoma is a surgical emergency due to the risk of septal cartilage necrosis and abscess formation."],"references":["Koh J, Bhatti O, Mahmood A, Agar N. Traumatic nasal injuries in general practice. Australian Family Physician. 2016;45:650-3. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27606367/","Gupta G, Mahajan K. Nasal Septal Hematoma. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470247/","Jackson R, Jia W, Edafe O. Evaluation of the management of nasal septal haematoma and abscess: a systematic review. J Laryngol Otol. 2025 Mar;139(3):153-159. doi: 10.1017/S0022215124001610. PMID: 39434415. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/39434415/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89450"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2324"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89450"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-24T16:05:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-24T16:06:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2324"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106986"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"item